        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity:
Based on our study of the MW (Sawada et al. 2012a), we expect that the diffuse emission in the inter-arm region and the bright emission in the spiral arm have the 12CO J=1-0 brightness temperatures of 3-5 and 10-20 K, respectively, at the velocity resolution of 2.6 km/s.  These correspond to 2.0-3.3 and 6.6-13 K in J=2-1, respectively, if the J=2-1/J=1-0 intensity ratio is 0.66 (Sakamoto et al. 1995).  The sensitivity of 0.4 K is required in order to detect the inter-arm diffuse emission at S/N &gt; 5.
Sakamoto et al. (2004) did not detect 1.3 mm continuum in the central 2 kpc of M83 in their SMA observations.  Their 5-sigma upper limit, 50 mJy/beam, is used as a rough estimate of the peak continuum flux.

Imaging:
We aim at the spatial resolution of 0.2" (4.4 pc), which is necessary to resolve the internal structure of molecular clouds, as discussed in the Scientific Justification.  The usage of the ACA is indispensable in order to detect faint and widespread emission, which is supposed to be the primary state of the gas in the inter-arm region.

Correlator Setup:
One of the basebands is assigned to the 12CO J=2-1 line.  The correlator mode is dual-polarization 937.5 MHz FDM, whose velocity coverage and resolution are 1220 and 0.64 km/s, respectively.  Since the line width of M83 is ~200 km/s as a whole (e.g., Kuno et al. 2007) and a few tens of km/s at each line of sight, the 1220 km/s coverage is sufficient for the baseline subtraction in the TP array.  The target velocity resolution is 2.6 km/s (the same as which we used in Sawada et al. 2012a) as described above.  However, the 0.64 km/s resolution of the correlator output will enable us to study the dynamical state of individual bright structures.  The size-linewidth relation of molecular clouds (e.g., Solomon et al. 1987) implies that a structure of 4.4 pc has a linewidth of ~2 km/s = 3 velocity resolution elements.
The other three basebands are configured to be dual-polarization TDM to observe continuum emission, as there are no bright lines which are simultaneously observable with the CO line.

